commit f4afbb0a5216f013309465a4a2b2c2815be35346
Author: Corey Thompson <coreyt@gmail.com>
Date:   Sun May 24 20:12:13 2026 -0500

    fix(ci): make cargo publish tiers idempotent for axis-W-only patches
    
    The 0.6.1 BUMP slice bumped axis-W to 0.6.1 while holding axis-E
    (fathomdb-embedder-api) at 0.6.0 per Wake d-001. release.yml T1
    (publish-rust-t1-embedder-api) ran `cargo publish` unconditionally,
    which would have failed with "version already exists" because
    crates.io already serves fathomdb-embedder-api@0.6.0 from the 0.6.0
    GA train.
    
    Fix: every publish tier (T1-T7) now delegates to a small helper,
    scripts/release/cargo-publish-if-new.sh, which queries the registry
    JSON API for the target crate version before publishing. If the
    version is already on crates.io the helper logs "already published;
    skipping" and exits 0; otherwise it execs `cargo publish -p <crate>
    --token "$CARGO_REGISTRY_TOKEN"`. With --dry-run the registry check
    is bypassed and the helper always forwards to `cargo publish
    --dry-run` so packaging stays exercised on dispatch rehearsals.
    
    Generalizes for future axis-W-only patches and for partial-republish
    retries (an RC2 following an RC1 that partially published no-ops
    cleanly on the already-published tiers).
    
    Version reader handles both `version = "X.Y.Z"` and `version.workspace
    = true` (resolved against the root Cargo.toml [workspace.package]).
    Pre-release tags (e.g. 0.6.1-rc.1) match via exact-string lookup in
    versions[].num — the registry returns all numbers, including
    pre-releases, so the skip path triggers for retried RC pushes too.
    Yanked versions are still treated as "already published" because
    cargo publish refuses to republish a yanked number.
    
    TDD: scripts/tests/test_cargo_publish_if_new.sh covers the skip,
    publish, pre-release skip, --dry-run, propagate-failure, missing-arg,
    and User-Agent-regression cases against a python3 http.server fixture
    with a cargo shim — fully offline, no real toolchain or registry
    hits. RED demonstrated before the helper existed.
    
    The sleep-60s index-propagation step still runs after a skip (it
    gates on dispatch dry_run, not on whether a publish actually
    happened). Slightly suboptimal but not incorrect; an optimization
    slice could gate the sleep on a step output if it ever matters.
    
    Unblocks 0.6.1-RC1.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>

