dev/plans/runs/C1-threadsafe2-rebuild-20260504T022727Z.log:662:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01X4DBSL1bVdWdiFyr1CFmcr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. The flag `-DSQLITE_THREADSAFE=1` is hardcoded at line 137. The `LIBSQLITE3_FLAGS` is applied AFTER at line 289. In GCC/Clang, when you have duplicate `-D` definitions for the same macro, the LAST one wins (since it's preprocessor command-line flags passed left to right, and the compiler processes them in order). So `-DSQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` after `-DSQLITE_THREADSAFE=1` should override it.\n\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how GCC handles macro redefinitions via command-line flags. The first definition typically takes precedence, not the last, and redefining a macro usually triggers a warning. Let me verify the exact behavior here.\n\nLooking at the GCC documentation more carefully, when you pass multiple `-D` flags with the same macro name but different values, the last one actually wins—each definition overrides the previous one. So `-DSQLITE_THREADSAFE=1 ... -DSQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` results in `THREADSAFE=2`. This might generate a compiler warning depending on the platform.\n\nThe Route 1 approach using `LIBSQLITE3_FLAGS` has a practical problem: it relies on an environment variable being set at build time, and if the build cache is warm without running `cargo clean`, those flags won't be reapplied.\n\nFor Route 2 with a `build.rs` script, I initially thought about using `cargo:rustc-env` to set the flags, but that only affects the current crate's environment, not dependent build scripts. The real challenge is propagating the configuration down to the sqlite3-sys build script, which would require either custom Cargo metadata or finding another way to pass the flags through the dependency chain. I'm realizing the build.rs approach won't easily pass environment variables down to dependent build scripts, so I need to weigh the pra